        "created_at": "2025-09-07T14:03:16.321Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I sometimes tap into a user chat on signal, and at the bottom, instead of the field to add a new message to the chat stream, it says “This person is no longer using Signal. Invite them to Signal to keep the conversation here.”</p>\n<p>This doesn’t necessarily mean they’ve stopped using Signal. It often happens when a friend gets a new phone, can’t figure out how to “transfer” their data from the old phone, and so creates a fresh registration and profile under their new number.  The point is I now have two chat streams for them, a live one under the new contact account/userId and a dead one, same name, under the old contact account/userId.  They used the same profile name and avatar for both (and represent the same person).</p>\n<p>But in the UI contact list (e.g. when I’m searching for a chat, or in the list where I’m sending a message to a user), <strong>their name appears twice, and the two avatars look identical</strong>.  One is usable for sending messages, one is not.</p>\n<p>My suggestion is that when the system notices that the a particular account has deregistered and is “not using signal”,  their Avatar image (picture or initials) is thereafter always overlayed with a big red X (or some other strong visible artifact) so I don’t needlessly tap on it to try to send a message to an account who no longer exists.  This would be done where ever the avatar is displayed (in lists, next to messages, at the top of their profile, etc).</p>",
